1184–after 1229","1181–Male":"1181–Deceased","1184–1229":"1184–1229","–Male":"Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1181–1246":"1181–1246","1200–1246":"1200–1246","1188–1208":"1188–1208","1163–Female":"1163–Deceased","about 1184":"about 1184","before November 1208":"before November 1208","1163":"1163","1184":"1184","1181":"1181","1215":"1215","after 1229":"after 1229","1224":"1224","1246":"1246","1200":"1200","1188":"1188","about 1202":"about 1202","about 1200":"about 1200","1208":"1208","1229":"1229","Tunstall, Lancashire, England":"Tunstall, Lancashire, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Austwick","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Austwick (WR Yorks)."],"variants":[{"name":"Ostick","meanings":["English:  see  Austwick  ."]},{"name":"Austick","meanings":["English:  see  Austwick  ."]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":31,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705188,"age":40,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Maud de Austwick was born about 1184, in Lancashire, England, her father, Akarias de Austwick, was -2 and her mother, Mrs. Akarias de Austwick, was 23. She married Thomas de Tunstall about 1202, in Lancashire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died after 1229, in her hometown."},"et":{"about 1184–after 1229":"umbes 1184–pärast 1229","1181–